Chatti. On these see Momms. 1. 1. pp. 149-152. They occupied the highland

tract, including the basin of the Eder and other tributaries of the upper Weser, where their name survives in the modern Hessen. They were not known to Caesar, unless they are his ‘Suebi‚’ but-except during the short supremacy of Arminius (566 e. 36, 1), they are the most constant and most powerful enemies of Rome in Western Germany, though their action is hampered by their feuds with their own neighbours the Cherusci (c. 36, 2, A. 12. 28, 2) and Hermunduri (A. 13. 57, 1). They had been lately the object of Domitian's attack (see on c. 29, 3), and continue to be heard of until they are absorbed into the Franks.
